1 WHEREAS, since 1945, the fraternity has undertaken a National Social Action
2 Program to meet the needs of African Americans in the areas of health, housing, civil rights,
3 and education, and has been a patron of the United Negro College Fund since 1955; and
4 WHEREAS, Omega Psi Phi men were actively involved in the fight to eliminate
5 racial discrimination; brothers Spottswood Robinson, Oliver Hill, and James Nabrit served
6 as part of the inner circle of the NAACP Legal Defense and Educational Fund, and Omega
7 men throughout the United States participated in sit-ins and other demonstrations central to
8 the civil rights struggle; and
9 WHEREAS, brother Grant Reynolds played a major role in President Truman's
10 landmark 1948 decision to desegregate the United States Armed Forces, and Brother Bayard
11 Rustin served as the chief organizer of the 1963 March on Washington for Jobs and
12 Freedom, which was one of the largest civil rights demonstrations in American history; and
13 WHEREAS, the roll of distinguished Omega members spans every sector of
14 American life, including Dr. Carter G. Woodson, the "Father of Black History";
15 Dr. Benjamin E. Mays, mentor to Dr. Martin Luther King Jr.; Dr. Charles Drew, who
16 revolutionized blood banking; and the Reverend Jesse L. Jackson, founder of Operation
17 PUSH and the National Rainbow Coalition; and
18 WHEREAS, Omega Psi Phi has maintained a proud and enduring presence in
19 Louisiana for over a century; the Rho Omega Chapter in Shreveport was established in
20 September 1923 and stands as the oldest graduate chapter in the Ninth District; the chapter
21 has made a tremendous impact on the social, economic, civic, and political life of its
22 community; and
23 WHEREAS, the Rho Phi Chapter, which is known as the "Crescent City Ques", was
24 established in New Orleans on October 1, 1927, and has enjoyed nearly one hundred years
25 of dedicated service to the Greater New Orleans community; and
26 WHEREAS, the Lambda Alpha Chapter was organized on May 8, 1936, in Baton
27 Rouge; in 1946, the chapter was at the forefront of forming the Baton Rouge Inter-Fraternal
28 Council, whose initial service projects included voter registration in the community and the
29 investigation of government housing for returning veterans; and
